commit.message: Changes update for 1.11

Do not scrape `const` modifier on char pointers corresponding to strings

Follow-up to d5d11eb.

Fix regression in parsing of `[string]` attribute

The check that it applies only to character arrays or pointers
was too strong and redundant with the one already there in normalize.ml.

Fixes: #23
Updates for release 1.10

Build and save HTML documentation in docs/ folder

For Github Pages integration
Resurrect the manual

Early allocation of Out dependent parameters that are pointers

Before, this was done only for In and InOut dependent parameters,
because Out parameters are allocated later.
However, this generates wrong code for `length_is(*m)` attributes.
Early allocation is safer.

Scrape `const` modifier within arrays

So that `const char x[]` becomes `char x[]` as expected.

Add `[bytes]` attribute for char arrays and pointers

This causes them to be mapped to OCaml's `bytes` type.
Use modern FFI function names, so as to support OCaml 5.00 (#22)

commit.message:
Touch up the comcomp example and build it only in Win32

It makes assumptions about C++ object layout that may be true under Windows,
but are not on other systems.

Cast "String_val(v)" to the expected C type

String_val returns a `const char *`, but the C type is ofter `char *`
and sometimes it's `unsigned char *`.
Update Changes for 1.09

Revert "Suggest to use 'cpp -traditional'"

This reverts commit 13f05c0dcdd58f82be8401437109b1cbe0d0a26a.

As shown by issue #18, "-traditional" has its own problems and
breaks IDL code that worked before.

commit.message: drop unresolvable IID_IUnknown symbol reference from runtime library on unix
Makefile: clean better
Have mercy and add a .gitignore
Use CAML_NAME_SPACE to detect uses of old FFI function names

Suggest to use 'cpp -traditional'

This works better for GCC and Clang.

In generated code, use caml_* names for FFI functions

E.g. 'modify' becomes 'caml_modify', 'Bigarray_val' becomes 'Caml_ba_array_val'.

Support "*var" in length_is and size_is attributes

Follow-up to 907190a.  The restriction to variables is too strong.
An example we want to support is "length_is(*outvar)" where "outvar"
is an out or in-out parameter.
